This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for imports, packages and bindings.

## Import model

Project source imports are module-root-relative.

- `@./` has no meaning.
- Parent traversal is invalid.
- Reaching a module or support package exposes only its `export:` facade.
- No import uses fallback precedence or nearest-match shadowing.

Header syntax records import shells. Stage 0 uses structural provider references. Interface binding later creates stable imported symbol bindings.

## Package model

- Normal modules are directory-scoped compilation units.
- Scoped `+*.bst` roots expose project-local support packages.
- The project-root facade exposes the external package surface.
- Dependency, Core and Builder source packages compile in separate graph boundaries.
- Binding-backed packages expose typed external symbols rather than source modules.
- `@project` is a reserved synthetic interface, not a normal package.

## Rewrite focus

Explain namespace design, visibility, re-export bindings, source versus binding-backed packages and why package origin is separate from backing.

Canonical details live in both architecture authorities.
